    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;">(In the school literature clubroom…)<br/><br/>Monika: “Okay, now that everyone’s here…who wants to share first?”<br/><br/>Natsuki: “Hmm, I guess I can go first. I’ve been working on a short story lately. It’s called ‘The Magical Bakery.’ It’s about a young girl who discovers a hidden bakery in the woods that grants wishes to those who truly believe in its magic.”<br/><br/>Sayori: “Ooh, that sounds enchanting, Natsuki! I can’t wait to read it.”<br/><br/>Yuri: “I agree, the concept sounds fascinating. I’m interested to see how you incorporate themes of belief and magic into your writing.”<br/><br/>Natsuki: “Thanks, guys. I’ll make sure to bring copies of it next time so you can all read it. Oh, and also…anyone want to hear a joke?”<br/><br/>Monika: “Oh dear god, not again…”<br/><br/>Sayori: “Natsuki, we’re trying to discuss literature here. And plus, your jokes always make me cringe.”<br/><br/>Natsuki: “Well…I’m telling it anyway. Why don’t skeletons fight each other?”<br/><br/>Yuri: “Here we go…”<br/><br/>Natsuki: “Because they don’t have the guts!”<br/><br/>Sayori: “Oh Natsuki, that one never gets old.”<br/><br/>Monika: “Alright, moving on. Yuri, would you like to share something with us?” (turning towards Yuri) “…Yuri?”<br/><br/>Yuri: (fast asleep due to Natsuki’s horrible joke)<br/><br/>Sayori: (giggles) “Yuri, wake up! It’s your turn to share something.”<br/><br/>Yuri: (jolts awake, still half-asleep) “Oh, I’m so sorry. I must have dozed off for a moment there. Um, yes, I do have something to share. Recently, I’ve been exploring the works of Edgar Allan Poe. His dark and melancholic writing has always intrigued me, and I’ve been particularly captivated by his poem, ‘The Raven’…”<br/><br/>(Yuri suddenly falls</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>off her chair, fully asleep)</p>
<p>Monika: (sighs) "Well, I suppose we'll have to wait for Yuri to wake up again. Sayori, how about you?"</p>
<p>Sayori: "Oh! Um, well, I haven't really been working on any writing lately...but I did find this really cute picture book at the library the other day. It's called 'The Adventures of Fluffy the Bunny.' It's about a fluffy bunny who goes on all sorts of fun adventures with his animal friends. It's such a heartwarming and adorable story!"</p>
<p>Natsuki: "That sounds like a book for little kids, Sayori. Are you sure you're not too old for that?"</p>
<p>Sayori: "Well, maybe, but I still enjoy reading cute and wholesome stories. They always put a smile on my face."</p>
<p>Monika: "That's a lovely sentiment, Sayori. It's important to find joy in the simple things. As for me, I've been working on a poem recently. It's about the beauty of nature and how it can bring us solace and peace in our busy lives."</p>
<p>Yuri: (finally waking up) "I'm so sorry for falling asleep, everyone. I must have been more tired than I realized. If you don't mind, I can share my thoughts on 'The Raven' another time."</p>
<p>Monika: "Of course, Yuri. We can always come back to your poem when you're fully awake. Does anyone have any questions or feedback for each other?"</p>
<p>(And so, the literature club meeting continues with discussions, laughter, and moments of inspiration, showcasing the unique talents and interests of its members.)</p></div>

