    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>In most professional sports leagues, there is usually a single draft that includes all eligible players regardless of their positions. This means that players from different positions, such as quarterbacks, wide receivers, and running backs in football, or forwards, centers, and guards in basketball, are all available for selection in the same draft. Teams can then choose players based on their specific needs and strategies. However, some sports leagues, like the National Hockey League (NHL), do conduct separate drafts for specific positions. For example, the NHL holds a separate draft specifically for goaltenders because the demand for this position is unique and teams may have specialized scouting and evaluation processes for selecting goalies.</p></div>

