    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Series resistance is when resistors are connected one after the other in a straight line or series. The total resistance in a series circuit is the sum of all the individual resistances. If one resistor fails or is removed from the circuit, the circuit is broken and no current flow.</p>
<p>Parallel resistance is when resistors are connected side by side. The total resistance in a parallel circuit is less than any of the individual resistances. If one resistor fails or is removed from the circuit, the current will still flow through the remaining resistors.</p></div>

